         <div type="apparatus">
            <app loc="147">
               <note>QUI F ANO, possible abbreviation for qui fuit annorum as attested to in two similary inscriptions discovered near Rome.  See CIL 06 14417:D(is) M(anibus) / Carpophoro / bene merenti / co(n)iugi q(ui) v(ixit) a(nnos) / mecum XI m(enses) IIII / qui f(uit) an(norum) XXXXII / Muna co(n)iux b(e)n(e) m(erenti) and ICUR-01 03455: Euschemon Graecus qui fuit annor(um) / XXX et vixit cum coniuge sua ann(os) II et / mens(es) VII et dies VI reliquit filium / mens(i)um III bene merenti con/iugi Ursa fecit deposit(us) XVIII / Kal(endas) Ian(uarias) et Sisinnius frater / cum amicis suis in pace / prid(ie) Idus Decemb(res) die Martis</note>
            </app>
            <app loc="150">
               <note>Here the craftsman likely meant cumquo instead of the qumquo.</note>
            </app>
         </div>
         <div type="translation" xml:lang="en">
            <p>To the Shades of the Underworld. Faustina (made this) for her most dear and well-deserving husband Primitivus, who was in his forieth year, with whom she lived twelve years , eight months, seven days; and also Felix and Maximinus students, made this for their well-deserving teacher.</p>
         </div>
